159SSL_HANDSHAKE::~SSL_HANDSHAKE() {
160 ssl->ctx->x509_method->hs_flush_cached_ca_names(this);
161}

163void SSL_HANDSHAKE::ResizeSecrets(size_t hash_len) {
164 if (hash_len > SSL_MAX_MD_SIZE) {
165 abort();
166 }
167 hash_len_ = hash_len;
168}
169
170bool SSL_HANDSHAKE::GetClientHello(SSLMessage *out_msg,
171 SSL_CLIENT_HELLO *out_client_hello) {
172 if (!ech_client_hello_buf.empty()) {
173 // If the backing buffer is non-empty, the ClientHelloInner has been set.
174 out_msg->is_v2_hello = false;
175 out_msg->type = SSL3_MT_CLIENT_HELLO;
176 out_msg->raw = CBS(ech_client_hello_buf);
177 out_msg->body = MakeConstSpan(ech_client_hello_buf).subspan(4);
178 } else if (!ssl->method->get_message(ssl, out_msg)) {
179 // The message has already been read, so this cannot fail.
180 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, ERR_R_INTERNAL_ERROR);
181 return false;
182 }
183
184 if (!ssl_client_hello_init(ssl, out_client_hello, out_msg->body)) {
185 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_CLIENTHELLO_PARSE_FAILED);
186 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL, SSL_AD_DECODE_ERROR);
187 return false;
188 }
189 return true;
190}
191
192UniquePtr<SSL_HANDSHAKE> ssl_handshake_new(SSL *ssl) {
193 UniquePtr<SSL_HANDSHAKE> hs = MakeUnique<SSL_HANDSHAKE>(ssl);
194 if (!hs || !hs->transcript.Init()) {
195 return nullptr;
196 }
197 hs->config = ssl->config.get();
198 if (!hs->config) {
199 assert(hs->config);
200 return nullptr;
201 }
202 return hs;
203}
204
205bool ssl_check_message_type(SSL *ssl, const SSLMessage &msg, int type) {
206 if (msg.type != type) {
207 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL, SSL_AD_UNEXPECTED_MESSAGE);
208 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_UNEXPECTED_MESSAGE);
209 ERR_add_error_dataf("got type %d, wanted type %d", msg.type, type);
210 return false;
211 }
212
213 return true;
214}
215
216bool ssl_add_message_cbb(SSL *ssl, CBB *cbb) {
217 Array<uint8_t> msg;
218 if (!ssl->method->finish_message(ssl, cbb, &msg) ||
219 !ssl->method->add_message(ssl, std::move(msg))) {
220 return false;
221 }
222
223 return true;
224}
225
226size_t ssl_max_handshake_message_len(const SSL *ssl) {
227 // kMaxMessageLen is the default maximum message size for handshakes which do
228 // not accept peer certificate chains.
229 static const size_t kMaxMessageLen = 16384;
230
231 if (SSL_in_init(ssl)) {
232 SSL_CONFIG *config = ssl->config.get(); // SSL_in_init() implies not NULL.
233 if ((!ssl->server || (config->verify_mode & SSL_VERIFY_PEER)) &&
234 kMaxMessageLen < ssl->max_cert_list) {
235 return ssl->max_cert_list;
236 }
237 return kMaxMessageLen;
238 }
239
240 if (ssl_protocol_version(ssl) < TLS1_3_VERSION) {
241 // In TLS 1.2 and below, the largest acceptable post-handshake message is
242 // a HelloRequest.
243 return 0;
244 }
245
246 if (ssl->server) {
247 // The largest acceptable post-handshake message for a server is a
248 // KeyUpdate. We will never initiate post-handshake auth.
249 return 1;
250 }
251
252 // Clients must accept NewSessionTicket, so allow the default size.
253 return kMaxMessageLen;
254}
255
256bool ssl_hash_message(SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs, const SSLMessage &msg) {
257 // V2ClientHello messages are pre-hashed.
258 if (msg.is_v2_hello) {
259 return true;
260 }
261
262 return hs->transcript.Update(msg.raw);
263}
264
265bool ssl_parse_extensions(const CBS *cbs, uint8_t *out_alert,
266 Span<const SSL_EXTENSION_TYPE> ext_types,
267 bool ignore_unknown) {
268 // Reset everything.
269 for (const SSL_EXTENSION_TYPE &ext_type : ext_types) {
270 *ext_type.out_present = false;
271 CBS_init(ext_type.out_data, nullptr, 0);
272 }
273
274 CBS copy = *cbs;
275 while (CBS_len(&copy) != 0) {
276 uint16_t type;
277 CBS data;
278 if (!CBS_get_u16(&copy, &type) ||
279 !CBS_get_u16_length_prefixed(&copy, &data)) {
280 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_PARSE_TLSEXT);
281 *out_alert = SSL_AD_DECODE_ERROR;
282 return false;
283 }
284
285 const SSL_EXTENSION_TYPE *found = nullptr;
286 for (const SSL_EXTENSION_TYPE &ext_type : ext_types) {
287 if (type == ext_type.type) {
288 found = &ext_type;
289 break;
290 }
291 }
292
293 if (found == nullptr) {
294 if (ignore_unknown) {
295 continue;
296 }
297 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_UNEXPECTED_EXTENSION);
298 *out_alert = SSL_AD_UNSUPPORTED_EXTENSION;
299 return false;
300 }
301
302 // Duplicate ext_types are forbidden.
303 if (*found->out_present) {
304 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_DUPLICATE_EXTENSION);
305 *out_alert = SSL_AD_ILLEGAL_PARAMETER;
306 return false;
307 }
308
309 *found->out_present = 1;
310 *found->out_data = data;
311 }
312
313 return true;
314}
315
316enum ssl_verify_result_t ssl_verify_peer_cert(SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs) {
317 SSL *const ssl = hs->ssl;
318 const SSL_SESSION *prev_session = ssl->s3->established_session.get();
319 if (prev_session != NULL) {
320 // If renegotiating, the server must not change the server certificate. See
321 // https://mitls.org/pages/attacks/3SHAKE. We never resume on renegotiation,
322 // so this check is sufficient to ensure the reported peer certificate never
323 // changes on renegotiation.
324 assert(!ssl->server);
325 if (sk_CRYPTO_BUFFER_num(prev_session->certs.get()) !=
326 sk_CRYPTO_BUFFER_num(hs->new_session->certs.get())) {
327 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_SERVER_CERT_CHANGED);
328 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL, SSL_AD_ILLEGAL_PARAMETER);
329 return ssl_verify_invalid;
330 }
331
332 for (size_t i = 0; i < sk_CRYPTO_BUFFER_num(hs->new_session->certs.get());
333 i++) {
334 const CRYPTO_BUFFER *old_cert =
335 sk_CRYPTO_BUFFER_value(prev_session->certs.get(), i);
336 const CRYPTO_BUFFER *new_cert =
337 sk_CRYPTO_BUFFER_value(hs->new_session->certs.get(), i);
338 if (CRYPTO_BUFFER_len(old_cert) != CRYPTO_BUFFER_len(new_cert) ||
339 OPENSSL_memcmp(CRYPTO_BUFFER_data(old_cert),
340 CRYPTO_BUFFER_data(new_cert),
341 CRYPTO_BUFFER_len(old_cert)) != 0) {
342 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_SERVER_CERT_CHANGED);
343 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL, SSL_AD_ILLEGAL_PARAMETER);
344 return ssl_verify_invalid;
345 }
346 }
347
348 // The certificate is identical, so we may skip re-verifying the
349 // certificate. Since we only authenticated the previous one, copy other
350 // authentication from the established session and ignore what was newly
351 // received.
352 hs->new_session->ocsp_response = UpRef(prev_session->ocsp_response);
353 hs->new_session->signed_cert_timestamp_list =
354 UpRef(prev_session->signed_cert_timestamp_list);
355 hs->new_session->verify_result = prev_session->verify_result;
356 return ssl_verify_ok;
357 }
358
359 uint8_t alert = SSL_AD_CERTIFICATE_UNKNOWN;
360 enum ssl_verify_result_t ret;
361 if (hs->config->custom_verify_callback != nullptr) {
362 ret = hs->config->custom_verify_callback(ssl, &alert);
363 switch (ret) {
364 case ssl_verify_ok:
365 hs->new_session->verify_result = X509_V_OK;
366 break;
367 case ssl_verify_invalid:
368 // If |SSL_VERIFY_NONE|, the error is non-fatal, but we keep the result.
369 if (hs->config->verify_mode == SSL_VERIFY_NONE) {
370 ERR_clear_error();
371 ret = ssl_verify_ok;
372 }
373 hs->new_session->verify_result = X509_V_ERR_APPLICATION_VERIFICATION;
374 break;
375 case ssl_verify_retry:
376 break;
377 }
378 } else {
379 ret = ssl->ctx->x509_method->session_verify_cert_chain(
380 hs->new_session.get(), hs, &alert)
381 ? ssl_verify_ok
382 : ssl_verify_invalid;
383 }
384
385 if (ret == ssl_verify_invalid) {
386 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_CERTIFICATE_VERIFY_FAILED);
387 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL, alert);
388 }
389
390 // Emulate OpenSSL's client OCSP callback. OpenSSL verifies certificates
391 // before it receives the OCSP, so it needs a second callback for OCSP.
392 if (ret == ssl_verify_ok && !ssl->server &&
393 hs->config->ocsp_stapling_enabled &&
394 ssl->ctx->legacy_ocsp_callback != nullptr) {
395 int cb_ret =
396 ssl->ctx->legacy_ocsp_callback(ssl, ssl->ctx->legacy_ocsp_callback_arg);
397 if (cb_ret <= 0) {
398 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_OCSP_CB_ERROR);
399 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL,
400 cb_ret == 0 ? SSL_AD_BAD_CERTIFICATE_STATUS_RESPONSE
401 : SSL_AD_INTERNAL_ERROR);
402 ret = ssl_verify_invalid;
403 }
404 }
405
406 return ret;
407}
408
409// Verifies a stored certificate when resuming a session. A few things are
410// different from verify_peer_cert:
411// 1. We can't be renegotiating if we're resuming a session.
412// 2. The session is immutable, so we don't support verify_mode ==
413// SSL_VERIFY_NONE
414// 3. We don't call the OCSP callback.
415// 4. We only support custom verify callbacks.
416enum ssl_verify_result_t ssl_reverify_peer_cert(SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs,
417 bool send_alert) {
418 SSL *const ssl = hs->ssl;
419 assert(ssl->s3->established_session == nullptr);
420 assert(hs->config->verify_mode != SSL_VERIFY_NONE);
421
422 uint8_t alert = SSL_AD_CERTIFICATE_UNKNOWN;
423 enum ssl_verify_result_t ret = ssl_verify_invalid;
424 if (hs->config->custom_verify_callback != nullptr) {
425 ret = hs->config->custom_verify_callback(ssl, &alert);
426 }
427
428 if (ret == ssl_verify_invalid) {
429 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_CERTIFICATE_VERIFY_FAILED);
430 if (send_alert) {
431 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL, alert);
432 }
433 }
434
435 return ret;
436}

438uint16_t ssl_get_grease_value(SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs,
439 enum ssl_grease_index_t index) {
440 // Draw entropy for all GREASE values at once. This avoids calling
441 // |RAND_bytes| repeatedly and makes the values consistent within a
442 // connection. The latter is so the second ClientHello matches after
443 // HelloRetryRequest and so supported_groups and key_shares are consistent.
444 if (!hs->grease_seeded) {
445 RAND_bytes(hs->grease_seed, sizeof(hs->grease_seed));
446 hs->grease_seeded = true;
447 }
448
449 // This generates a random value of the form 0xωaωa, for all 0 ≤ ω < 16.
450 uint16_t ret = hs->grease_seed[index];
451 ret = (ret & 0xf0) | 0x0a;
452 ret |= ret << 8;
453 return ret;
454}
455
456enum ssl_hs_wait_t ssl_get_finished(SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs) {
457 SSL *const ssl = hs->ssl;
458 SSLMessage msg;
459 if (!ssl->method->get_message(ssl, &msg)) {
460 return ssl_hs_read_message;
461 }
462
463 if (!ssl_check_message_type(ssl, msg, SSL3_MT_FINISHED)) {
464 return ssl_hs_error;
465 }
466
467 // Snapshot the finished hash before incorporating the new message.
468 uint8_t finished[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
469 size_t finished_len;
470 if (!hs->transcript.GetFinishedMAC(finished, &finished_len,
471 ssl_handshake_session(hs), !ssl->server) ||
472 !ssl_hash_message(hs, msg)) {
473 return ssl_hs_error;
474 }
475
476 int finished_ok = CBS_mem_equal(&msg.body, finished, finished_len);
477#if defined(BORINGSSL_UNSAFE_FUZZER_MODE)
478 finished_ok = 1;
479#endif
480 if (!finished_ok) {
481 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL, SSL_AD_DECRYPT_ERROR);
482 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_DIGEST_CHECK_FAILED);
483 return ssl_hs_error;
484 }
485
486 // Copy the Finished so we can use it for renegotiation checks.
487 if (finished_len > sizeof(ssl->s3->previous_client_finished) ||
488 finished_len > sizeof(ssl->s3->previous_server_finished)) {
489 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, ERR_R_INTERNAL_ERROR);
490 return ssl_hs_error;
491 }
492
493 if (ssl->server) {
494 OPENSSL_memcpy(ssl->s3->previous_client_finished, finished, finished_len);
495 ssl->s3->previous_client_finished_len = finished_len;
496 } else {
497 OPENSSL_memcpy(ssl->s3->previous_server_finished, finished, finished_len);
498 ssl->s3->previous_server_finished_len = finished_len;
499 }
500
501 // The Finished message should be the end of a flight.
502 if (ssl->method->has_unprocessed_handshake_data(ssl)) {
503 ssl_send_alert(ssl, SSL3_AL_FATAL, SSL_AD_UNEXPECTED_MESSAGE);
504 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_EXCESS_HANDSHAKE_DATA);
505 return ssl_hs_error;
506 }
507
508 ssl->method->next_message(ssl);
509 return ssl_hs_ok;
510}
511
512bool ssl_send_finished(SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs) {
513 SSL *const ssl = hs->ssl;
514 const SSL_SESSION *session = ssl_handshake_session(hs);
515
516 uint8_t finished[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
517 size_t finished_len;
518 if (!hs->transcript.GetFinishedMAC(finished, &finished_len, session,
519 ssl->server)) {
520 return 0;
521 }
522
523 // Log the master secret, if logging is enabled.
524 if (!ssl_log_secret(ssl, "CLIENT_RANDOM",
525 MakeConstSpan(session->secret, session->secret_length))) {
526 return 0;
527 }
528
529 // Copy the Finished so we can use it for renegotiation checks.
530 if (finished_len > sizeof(ssl->s3->previous_client_finished) ||
531 finished_len > sizeof(ssl->s3->previous_server_finished)) {
532 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, ERR_R_INTERNAL_ERROR);
533 return 0;
534 }
535
536 if (ssl->server) {
537 OPENSSL_memcpy(ssl->s3->previous_server_finished, finished, finished_len);
538 ssl->s3->previous_server_finished_len = finished_len;
539 } else {
540 OPENSSL_memcpy(ssl->s3->previous_client_finished, finished, finished_len);
541 ssl->s3->previous_client_finished_len = finished_len;
542 }
543
544 ScopedCBB cbb;
545 CBB body;
546 if (!ssl->method->init_message(ssl, cbb.get(), &body, SSL3_MT_FINISHED) ||
547 !CBB_add_bytes(&body, finished, finished_len) ||
548 !ssl_add_message_cbb(ssl, cbb.get())) {
549 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, ERR_R_INTERNAL_ERROR);
550 return 0;
551 }
552
553 return 1;
554}
555
556bool ssl_output_cert_chain(SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs) {
557 ScopedCBB cbb;
558 CBB body;
559 if (!hs->ssl->method->init_message(hs->ssl, cbb.get(), &body,
560 SSL3_MT_CERTIFICATE) ||
561 !ssl_add_cert_chain(hs, &body) ||
562 !ssl_add_message_cbb(hs->ssl, cbb.get())) {
563 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, ERR_R_INTERNAL_ERROR);
564 return false;
565 }
566
567 return true;
568}
569
570const SSL_SESSION *ssl_handshake_session(const SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs) {
571 if (hs->new_session) {
572 return hs->new_session.get();
573 }
574 return hs->ssl->session.get();
575}
576
577int ssl_run_handshake(SSL_HANDSHAKE *hs, bool *out_early_return) {
578 SSL *const ssl = hs->ssl;
579 for (;;) {
580 // Resolve the operation the handshake was waiting on. Each condition may
581 // halt the handshake by returning, or continue executing if the handshake
582 // may immediately proceed. Cases which halt the handshake can clear
583 // |hs->wait| to re-enter the state machine on the next iteration, or leave
584 // it set to keep the condition sticky.
585 switch (hs->wait) {
586 case ssl_hs_error:
587 ERR_restore_state(hs->error.get());
588 return -1;
589
590 case ssl_hs_flush: {
591 int ret = ssl->method->flush_flight(ssl);
592 if (ret <= 0) {
593 return ret;
594 }
595 break;
596 }
597
598 case ssl_hs_read_server_hello:
599 case ssl_hs_read_message:
600 case ssl_hs_read_change_cipher_spec: {
601 if (ssl->quic_method) {
602 // QUIC has no ChangeCipherSpec messages.
603 assert(hs->wait != ssl_hs_read_change_cipher_spec);
604 // The caller should call |SSL_provide_quic_data|. Clear |hs->wait| so
605 // the handshake can check if there is sufficient data next iteration.
606 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_WANT_READ;
607 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
608 return -1;
609 }
610
611 uint8_t alert = SSL_AD_DECODE_ERROR;
612 size_t consumed = 0;
613 ssl_open_record_t ret;
614 if (hs->wait == ssl_hs_read_change_cipher_spec) {
615 ret = ssl_open_change_cipher_spec(ssl, &consumed, &alert,
616 ssl->s3->read_buffer.span());
617 } else {
618 ret = ssl_open_handshake(ssl, &consumed, &alert,
619 ssl->s3->read_buffer.span());
620 }
621 if (ret == ssl_open_record_error &&
622 hs->wait == ssl_hs_read_server_hello) {
623 uint32_t err = ERR_peek_error();
624 if (ERR_GET_LIB(err) == ERR_LIB_SSL &&
625 ERR_GET_REASON(err) == SSL_R_SSLV3_ALERT_HANDSHAKE_FAILURE) {
626 // Add a dedicated error code to the queue for a handshake_failure
627 // alert in response to ClientHello. This matches NSS's client
628 // behavior and gives a better error on a (probable) failure to
629 // negotiate initial parameters. Note: this error code comes after
630 // the original one.
631 //
632 // See https://crbug.com/446505.
633 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(SSL, SSL_R_HANDSHAKE_FAILURE_ON_CLIENT_HELLO);
634 }
635 }
636 bool retry;
637 int bio_ret = ssl_handle_open_record(ssl, &retry, ret, consumed, alert);
638 if (bio_ret <= 0) {
639 return bio_ret;
640 }
641 if (retry) {
642 continue;
643 }
644 ssl->s3->read_buffer.DiscardConsumed();
645 break;
646 }
647
648 case ssl_hs_read_end_of_early_data: {
649 if (ssl->s3->hs->can_early_read) {
650 // While we are processing early data, the handshake returns early.
651 *out_early_return = true;
652 return 1;
653 }
654 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
655 break;
656 }
657
658 case ssl_hs_certificate_selection_pending:
659 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_PENDING_CERTIFICATE;
660 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
661 return -1;
662
663 case ssl_hs_handoff:
664 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_HANDOFF;
665 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
666 return -1;
667
668 case ssl_hs_handback: {
669 int ret = ssl->method->flush_flight(ssl);
670 if (ret <= 0) {
671 return ret;
672 }
673 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_HANDBACK;
674 hs->wait = ssl_hs_handback;
675 return -1;
676 }
677
678 // The following cases are associated with callback APIs which expect to
679 // be called each time the state machine runs. Thus they set |hs->wait|
680 // to |ssl_hs_ok| so that, next time, we re-enter the state machine and
681 // call the callback again.
682 case ssl_hs_x509_lookup:
683 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_WANT_X509_LOOKUP;
684 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
685 return -1;
686 case ssl_hs_channel_id_lookup:
687 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_WANT_CHANNEL_ID_LOOKUP;
688 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
689 return -1;
690 case ssl_hs_private_key_operation:
691 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_WANT_PRIVATE_KEY_OPERATION;
692 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
693 return -1;
694 case ssl_hs_pending_session:
695 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_PENDING_SESSION;
696 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
697 return -1;
698 case ssl_hs_pending_ticket:
699 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_PENDING_TICKET;
700 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
701 return -1;
702 case ssl_hs_certificate_verify:
703 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_WANT_CERTIFICATE_VERIFY;
704 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
705 return -1;
706
707 case ssl_hs_early_data_rejected:
708 assert(ssl->s3->early_data_reason != ssl_early_data_unknown);
709 assert(!hs->can_early_write);
710 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_EARLY_DATA_REJECTED;
711 return -1;
712
713 case ssl_hs_early_return:
714 *out_early_return = true;
715 hs->wait = ssl_hs_ok;
716 return 1;
717
718 case ssl_hs_hints_ready:
719 ssl->s3->rwstate = SSL_ERROR_HANDSHAKE_HINTS_READY;
720 return -1;
721
722 case ssl_hs_ok:
723 break;
724 }
725
726 // Run the state machine again.
727 hs->wait = ssl->do_handshake(hs);
728 if (hs->wait == ssl_hs_error) {
729 hs->error.reset(ERR_save_state());
730 return -1;
731 }
732 if (hs->wait == ssl_hs_ok) {
733 // The handshake has completed.
734 *out_early_return = false;
735 return 1;
736 }
737
738 // Otherwise, loop to the beginning and resolve what was blocking the
739 // handshake.
740 }
741}
